                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13017691" author="jbellis" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 22:12:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;are you using sun jdk?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017695" author="xedin" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 22:17:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;no, I installed OpenJDK using apt-get `apt-get install openjdk-6-jdk openjdk-6-jre`&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017705" author="jbellis" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 22:24:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;give sun jdk a try.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017707" author="xedin" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 22:26:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ok, I will give it a try and comment back!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017739" author="xedin" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 23:14:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Works with Sun JDK&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;java version &quot;1.6.0_24&quot;
Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.6.0_24-b07)
Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 19.1-b02, mixed mode)
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But this could be a problem if, for example, Whirr sets up openjdk instead of one from the Sun, I will check that ASAP and comment...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017746" author="jbellis" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 23:23:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looks like this isn&apos;t the only time someone has seen segfaults due to using javaagent with OpenJDK: &lt;a href=&quot;http://liteforums.appdynamics.com/discussion/143/appagent-causing-segfault/p1&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://liteforums.appdynamics.com/discussion/143/appagent-causing-segfault/p1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would prefer to fix by changing our packaging to explicitly use Sun JDK instead of &quot;whatever.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Would also be useful to try w/ the IBM JDK: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/java/jdk/linux/download.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/java/jdk/linux/download.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13017747" author="xedin" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 23:26:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thats a good idea, I agree! Let me test IBM JDK tomorrow...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018096" author="jbellis" created="Sun, 10 Apr 2011 15:23:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Also jrockit: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/middleware/jrockit/downloads/index.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/middleware/jrockit/downloads/index.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018117" author="xedin" created="Sun, 10 Apr 2011 17:44:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Latest code (branch trunk) works with JRockit (jrockit-jdk1.6.0_22-R28.1.1-4.0.1) but note that JVM does not support following options: -Xmn&amp;lt;size&amp;gt; -XX:ThreadPriorityPolicy -XX:+UseParNewGC -XX:+UseConcMarkSweepGC -XX:+CMSParallelRemarkEnabled -XX:SurvivorRatio=8  -XX:MaxTenuringThreshold=1 -XX:CMSInitiatingOccupancyFraction=75 -XX:+UseCMSInitiatingOccupancyOnly&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018127" author="xedin" created="Sun, 10 Apr 2011 18:23:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;using IBM JDK started without any changes to the conf/cassandra-env.sh and everything worked fine.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;java version &quot;1.6.0&quot;
Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build pxi3260sr9fp1-20110208_03(SR9 FP1))
IBM J9 VM (build 2.4, JRE 1.6.0 IBM J9 2.4 Linux x86-32 jvmxi3260sr9-20110203_74623 (JIT enabled, AOT enabled)
J9VM - 20110203_074623
JIT  - r9_20101028_17488ifx3
GC   - 20101027_AA)
JCL  - 20110203_01
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018183" author="jbellis" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 03:11:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So, definitely an OpenJDK-only bug.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll see if I can give it a no-java-agent mode so we can limp along without it for OpenJDK.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018271" author="xedin" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 10:23:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018524" author="jbellis" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 19:28:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;attached.  (requires jamm 0.2.1 in lib/, also attached.)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(most of the patch is svn deleting the 0.2 jar.  silly svn.)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018550" author="jbellis" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 20:21:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;On Brandon&apos;s advice I moved the entire warning into the log4j call, even though this makes it unwieldy and we don&apos;t have perfect information as to what the cause is at that point.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018557" author="xedin" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 20:32:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Can you please re-attach git apply and patch both say that patch is corrupted at line 90?..&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018561" author="jbellis" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 20:51:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;manually ripped the binary portion out of the patch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018566" author="xedin" created="Mon, 11 Apr 2011 21:00:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018856" author="jbellis" created="Tue, 12 Apr 2011 15:09:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;committed&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13018900" author="hudson" created="Tue, 12 Apr 2011 16:42:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Integrated in Cassandra-0.8 #2 (See &lt;a href=&quot;https://hudson.apache.org/hudson/job/Cassandra-0.8/2/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://hudson.apache.org/hudson/job/Cassandra-0.8/2/&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br/&gt;
    hack to allow OpenJDK to run w/o javaagent (otherwise it segfaults)&lt;br/&gt;
patch by jbellis and brandonwilliams; reviewed by Pavel Yaskevich for &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-2441&quot; title=&quot;Cassandra crashes with segmentation fault on Debian 5.0 and Ubuntu 10.10&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-2441&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-2441&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13252306" author="richardlow" created="Thu, 12 Apr 2012 09:42:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Tracked this down to the stack size setting.  In cassandra-env.sh, the stack size is set to 128k.  From running gdb, the segfault is tracked down to a stack overflow in parse_manifest.c:234 within openjdk.  It&apos;s clear what&apos;s going on: there&apos;s a huge statically allocated variable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Setting the stack size to 256k means Cassandra can start up with javaagent.  So we could reenable this for openjdk if people are prepared to take the memory hit on stack size.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13467784" author="amram99" created="Tue, 2 Oct 2012 15:22:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Richard! Changing the stack size from 180k to 256k worked for me on Ubuntu 12.04 with Cassandra 1.1.5 and OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM/1.6.0_24&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13473605" author="alexiswilke" created="Wed, 10 Oct 2012 22:07:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I can confirm Bubba Gump comment. I have the same setup and increasing the stack solved the crash issue with OpenJDK.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13475992" author="mauzhang" created="Mon, 15 Oct 2012 06:18:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;180k works fine with OpenJDK 1.7.0_07. So update OpenJDK could be an option&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
